00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.849
Capital Gains Tax When Selling a
Home Owned Less Than Two Years.

00:00:04.400 --> 00:00:06.890
When selling a home you have
owned for less than two years,

00:00:07.120 --> 00:00:08.800
capital gains tax may apply.

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:13.910
This is general information only
and not legal or financial advice.

00:00:14.509 --> 00:00:18.280
Consult a CPA or attorney for
guidance specific to your situation.

00:00:18.875 --> 00:00:22.835
Capital gains is the profit you make
after subtracting what you paid for the

00:00:22.835 --> 00:00:25.724
home, plus improvements and selling costs.

00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:29.980
The IRS has a rule that lets you
avoid this tax if you owned and

00:00:29.980 --> 00:00:32.780
lived in the home for at least
two of the last five years.

00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:38.150
If you sell before meeting that rule,
the exclusion usually does not apply.

00:00:39.050 --> 00:00:41.629
If you owned the home for less
than one year, the profit is

00:00:41.629 --> 00:00:43.129
taxed like regular income.

00:00:44.325 --> 00:00:48.255
If you owned it for more than one
year but less than two, it is taxed

00:00:48.255 --> 00:00:49.915
at long-term capital gains rates.

00:00:51.012 --> 00:00:54.902
Texas does not have a state income
tax, but federal taxes may still apply.

00:00:56.162 --> 00:01:00.622
In some cases, a partial tax break may
be available for job changes, health

00:01:00.622 --> 00:01:02.652
issues, or other unexpected events.

00:01:03.500 --> 00:01:06.450
Talking with a tax professional
or attorney before selling

00:01:06.450 --> 00:01:07.809
is always a smart move.

